The new algorithm will adapt to DFI tole: The new algorithm will adapt to DFI tolerance to choose the parameters for each frame. IMPORTANT: The algorithm is optimized to maintain a balance between deflicking and corruption, so that it is easier to use StableDiffusion at low denoising to reconstruct lost detail while preserving the stability gained.
A noisy source can interfere with the ac: A noisy source can interfere with the accuracy of the scan. This will reduce noise, but also detail. However, this does not affect the original, and sometimes flatter images are not bad for the process, although you may need to balance by reducing the DFI tolerance.
Determines the movement tolerance of the: Determines the movement tolerance of the scan. Low tolerance will detect even small changes in static areas. High values will detect less movements. Ideally, it should detect the movements that are important to you, and skip the static and useless areas, reducing the flick in those.
This parameter commands the new dynamic: This parameter commands the new dynamic algorithm.
DFI expand fattens the edges of the area: DFI expand fattens the edges of the areas detected by DFI. Note: DFI tolerance modifies the amount of movement detected. This only affects that result, be it big or small. Its a complementary parameter. 0=Off.
Here you can check examples of the motio: Here you can check examples of the motion map for those parameters. It is useful, for example, to adjust denoise if you see that it detects unnecessary graininess. Keep in mind that what you see represents movement between two frames.
The black is basically what it won't pro: The black is basically what it won't process (it will let it through to preserve the movement), and the white what it will try to keep stable in that frame interpolation. Try freely. Here you can also test how the manual smooth works (advanced section).
Reduces render pixelation generated by c: Reduces render pixelation generated by corruption. However, be careful. It's resource hungry, and might remove excess detail. Not recommended to change size or FPD, but to use Stable Diffusion to remove the pixelation later.
Fine tunes the dynamic blur algorithm fo: Fine tunes the dynamic blur algorithm for DFI map. Lower = Stronger blur effects. Between 2-3 recommended.
To reduce the distortion generated by th: To reduce the distortion generated by the process, you can recover original information every X number of frames. Lower number = faster refresh.
Here you decide how much corruption keep: Here you decide how much corruption keep in each corruption refresh. Low values will recover more of the original frame, with its changes and flickering, in exchange for reducing corruption. You must find the balance that works best for your goal.
This smoothes the edges of the interpola: This smoothes the edges of the interpolated areas. Low values are currently recommended until the algorithm is updated.
The new dynamic algorithm will handle th: The new dynamic algorithm will handle these parameters. Activate them only for manual control.
I made this series of deflickers based o: I made this series of deflickers based on the standard that Vegas Pro includes. You can use them together or separately. Be careful when mixing them.
Blends a percentage between frames. This: Blends a percentage between frames. This can soften transitions and highlights. 50 is half of each frame. 80 or 20 are recommended values.
Use the overlay image blending mode. Not: Use the overlay image blending mode. Note that it works particularly good at mid-high values, wich will modify the overall contrast. You will have to decide what works for you.
Calculates the average between frames to: Calculates the average between frames to merge them. It may be more practical if you don't have a specific Blend deflicker value in mind.
With this you can merge two sets of fram: With this you can merge two sets of frames with overlay technique. For example, you can take a style video that is just lights and/or colors, and overlay it on top of another video.
The resulting video will be useful for u: The resulting video will be useful for use in Img2Img Batch and that the AI render preserves these added color and lighting details, along with the details of the original video.
DFI processing analyzes the motion of th: DFI processing analyzes the motion of the original video, and attempts to force that information into the generated video. Demo on https://github.com/AbyszOne/Abysz-LAB-Ext
In short, this will reduce flicker in ar: In short, this will reduce flicker in areas of the video that don't need to change, but SD does. For example, for a man smoking, leaning against a pole, it will detect that the pole is static, and will try to prevent it from changing as much as possible.
This is an aggressive process that requi: This is an aggressive process that requires a lot of control for each context. Read the recommended strategies.
Although Video to Video is the most effi: Although Video to Video is the most efficient way, a DFI One Shot method is under experimental development as well.
If you get enough understanding of the t: If you get enough understanding of the tool, you can achieve a much more stable and clean enough rendering. However, this is quite demanding.
Instead, a much friendlier and faster wa: Instead, a much friendlier and faster way to use this tool is as an intermediate step. For this, you can allow a reasonable degree of corruption in exchange for more general stability.
You can then clean up the corruption and: You can then clean up the corruption and recover details with a second step in Stable Diffusion at low denoising (0.2-0.4), using the same parameters and seed.
In this way, the final result will have: In this way, the final result will have the stability that we have gained, maintaining final detail. If you find a balanced workflow, you will get something at least much more coherent and stable than the raw AI render.
